1. How would you handle seasonal bursts?
Scenarios like Promotional campaign burst etc.
i. Horizontal scaling of consumers for higher parallelization.
ii. Tenant and Resource Isolation. No single system should be able to bring down the whole infra. Popularly known as the Celebrity problem.
iii. Delay in Processing + Resource based horizontal scaling.
iv. Queue based input provides an automatic backpressure by default.
2. How are we handling hot shards?
If a single tenant becomes too busy and is deployed in the common infra, it can lead to a hot shard issue.
i. Distribute keys better like tenantId#requestId
ii. Cache Mechanism based on frequency of calls.
3. What is the requirement of Long term + Short term poller configuration?
Any TTL based record expiry solution have their own limits. DynamoDB has a TTL SLA of 48hrs. So any event which has to be scheduled less
than 48 hrs in time will go to the Short term queue and be constantly pushed into the SQS via the Short term poller. We utilize the Visibility
Timeout feature of SQS in this case. Alternatively, if you are not in the AWS Ecosystem, Apache Pulsar provides you the same functionality.
If the event exceeds a 48hr scheduling window, we keep 2 records in the DB (First one for expiry with TTL, Second one as a log). The first record
after expiry is picked up into the DDB Stream -> Lambda -> SQS -> Long term poller -> Destination.
